      <byline class="print_byline">By PATRICIA JONAS</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Jonas, Patricia</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Inspect plants for pests in fall before pruning (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Monitor for pests: without the distraction of leaves, you can inspect twigs, branches and trunks of trees and shrubs for egg masses, scale and borer holes. Use binoculars to check treetops. Piles of sawdust may indicate feeding borer larvae; look for pencil-diameter holes in the bark, and prune out infested branches where possible.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Monitor for pests: without the distraction of leaves, you can inspect twigs, branches and trunks of trees and shrubs for egg masses, scale and borer holes. Use binoculars to check treetops. Piles of sawdust may indicate feeding borer larvae; look for pencil-diameter holes in the bark, and prune out infested branches where possible.</p>
        <p>Do not prune if you observe large (half an inch in diameter), perfectly round holes in maple, birch, elm or horse chestnut, favored species for Asian long-horned beetles. Report immediately to (800) 554-4501, ext. 72087, or (800) 201-7275.</p>
        <p>PATRICIA JONAS</p>
        <p>CUTTINGS: THIS WEEK</p>
      </block>
